{{Infobox company | name = Esko | logo = Logo-esko.png |type = Subsidiary of [[Danaher Corporation]] (NYSE: DHR) | foundation = [[Ghent]], [[Belgium]] (2002) | location_city = [[Ghent]] | location_country = [[Belgium]] | key_people = [[Udo Panenka]], [[CEO]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.labelsandlabeling.com/news/appointments/udo-panenka-named-new-president-esko |title=Udo Panenka named new president of Esko &#124; Labels & Labeling x|website=Labelsandlabeling.com |date=2014-11-19 |accessdate=2016-08-08}}</ref> | num_employees = 1800 (2018) | industry = [[Graphic arts]] | homepage = {{URL|www.esko.com}} }}
'''Esko''', formerly called ''EskoArtwork'', is a [[graphic arts]] company producing [[prepress]] [[Computer software|software]] and [[computer hardware|hardware]] for the packaging and labels, sign and display and publishing industries.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.i-grafix.com/contributed/andrew-tribute/a-business-model-for-the-future/ |title=A business model for the future - Print News &#124; Packaging News &#124; Wide Format news &#124; Print &#124; i-grafix &#124; Australia, New Zealand and Asia |website=I-grafix.com |date= |accessdate=2016-08-08}}</ref>
==History== Esko was the result of a [[merger]] between ''[[Barco (manufacturer)|Barco]] Graphics'' and ''[[Purup-Eskofot A/S]]'' in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barco.com/en/News/Press-releases/barco-graphics-and-purup-eskofot-to-merge.aspx |title=Graphics and Purup-Eskofot to merge |website=Barco.com |date=2001-09-07 |accessdate=2016-08-08}}</ref> The merged company was called Esko-Graphics but was renamed Esko in 2006. In the fall of 2005, Esko became fully owned by [[Axcel A/S]], a [[Denmark|Danish]] private [[equity investment]] company.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.axcel.dk/content/dk/presse/2005/esko-graphics_continues_packaging_growth_strategy |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-01-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100409145158/http://www.axcel.dk/content/dk/presse/2005/esko-graphics_continues_packaging_growth_strategy |archivedate=2010-04-09 |df= }}</ref>
In August 2007 Esko announced that it was 'joining forces' <ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.packagedesignmag.com/content/esko-and-artwork-systems-join-forces-consolidate-packaging-strengths |title=Esko and Artwork Systems to Join Forces to Consolidate Packaging Strengths &#124; Package Design |website=Packagedesignmag.com |date=2009-10-19 |accessdate=2016-08-08}}</ref> with Artwork Systems Group NV (AWS), its chief competitor in the packaging prepress market.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.i-grafix.com/contributed/andrew-tribute/package-deal/ |title=Package deal - Print News &#124; Packaging News &#124; Wide Format news &#124; Print &#124; i-grafix &#124; Australia, New Zealand and Asia |website=I-grafix.com |date= |accessdate=2016-08-08}}</ref> Esko initially bought 76.69% of AWS shares for €196 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.labelandnarrowweb.com/contents/view_breaking-news/2007-08-02/esko-acquires-artwork-systems/ |title=Esko Acquires Artwork Systems |publisher=Label and Narrow Web |date= |accessdate=2016-08-08}}</ref> Enfocus, a brand of [[PDF]] pre-flighting and workflow software originally acquired by Artwork Systems in 2000, became a subsidiary of the combined EskoArtwork company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetpdf.com/mainpage.asp?webpageid=736 |title=Classic PitStop developer Enfocus Software acquired by Artwork Systems |website=Planetpdf.com |date=2016-04-11 |accessdate=2016-08-08}}</ref>
Reflecting the merger, Esko changed its name to EskoArtwork. It also introduced a new logo, though it is visually very close to the Esko original.
In January 2011, 100% of EskoArtwork shares have been transferred to [[Danaher Corporation|Danaher]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Will Daley |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-01-20/danaher-agrees-to-buy-belgian-software-maker-eskoartwork-for-470-million.html |title=Danaher to Acquire EskoArtwork for 350 Million Euros |publisher=Bloomberg |date=2011-01-20 |accessdate=2016-08-08}}</ref> In January 2012, the name changed back to Esko, the logo was also updated. Esko acquired CAPE Systems<ref>https://www.flexography.org/industry-news/esko-buys-cape-systems/</ref> (a palletization software vendor) in 2013, MediaBeacon<ref>http://whattheythink.com/news/72839-esko-acquire-mediabeacon/</ref> (a [[Digital Asset Management]] vendor) in 2015 and Blue Software, LLC<ref>https://graphicartsmag.com/news/2018/07/esko-acquires-blue-software/</ref> (a label and artwork management software vendor) in 2018.
Esko is headquartered in [[Ghent]], [[Belgium]].
